<h4>Aggro Radii and Pets</h4>

<h3>Disclaimer</h3>

<p>
Verant doesn't completely document how aggro works.&nbsp; This discussion seeks
to explain observations of aggro radii and how the game works.&nbsp; Remember
that most mythology was at one time believed to explain real world observations!</p>

<h3>
Introduction</h3>
<p>At first glance, magicians have more to be concerned about with aggro radii
than most other classes since mages have pets.&nbsp; After all, either the mage
or the pet could cross into an aggro radius of a mob at any point.&nbsp; Use the
following legend in the examples:</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>M</b> as the Magician's position</li>
  <li><b>P</b> as the Pet's position</li>
  <li><b>X</b> or <b>Y</b> as a mob's position</li>
</ul>
<p>Observation suggests that each mob may in fact have up to 3
different radii:</p>
<ol>
  <li>the maximum distance at which it will decide to initiate an attack</li>
  <li>the maximum distance which the mob can shout to call for help from other
    mobs</li>
  <li>the maximum distance a mob will allow between itself and its target before
    giving up the chase</li>
</ol>
<p>In this illustration, only #1 and #2 are discussed.&nbsp; #3 is fairly
obvious (not all mobs have this radius).&nbsp;&nbsp; The radius for #2 is
typically larger than #1.&nbsp; That is, a mob can call for help further than it
is willing to initiate an attack on its own.&nbsp; How much larger depends on the mob.&nbsp; The only way to
gauge these radii is by experience fighting a given mob.&nbsp; The following is a
generalized discussion.&nbsp; The size of the circles is relative, but not
necessarily representative of any particular mob.&nbsp; </p>
<ul>
  <li><font color="#FF6600">Orange</font> circles are used to indicate #1 above
    - this mob is
    not attacking, but will attack a hostile target that enters the circle</li>
  <li><font color="#FF0000">Red</font> circles are used to indicate that a mob
    is attacking and actively calling for assistance (#2 above)</li>
</ul>
<h3><b>Key Terms</b></h3>
<div align="center">
  <center>
  <table border="0">
    <tr>
      <td valign="top"><i>Social </i></td>
      <td valign="top">
        <blockquote>
          <p>a mob that can communicate a need for assistance to other mobs of
          its type - socials mobs are usually (but not always) of the same
          species.&nbsp; For example, an orc will help another orc and a wasp
          will help another wasp, but orcs and wasps will not help each other.&nbsp; Again, there are exceptions.&nbsp; 
			There is no way to list them all here, but generally mobs are increasingly social as they increase in level.</p>
        </blockquote>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td valign="top"><i>Sympathetic</i></td>
      <td>
        <blockquote>
          <p>a mob that will help another mob.&nbsp; Using the above
          description, orcs are social and sympathetic to other orcs.&nbsp; Orcs
          are social, but not sympathetic to wasps.</p>
        </blockquote>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  </center>
</div>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Generally Understood</h3>
  <p>The following rules about aggro should already be generally understood and
  are not discussed below:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Some mobs will ignore hostile players standing within their aggro
    radius.&nbsp; The decision to ignore a hostile target is based on level and
    posture.&nbsp; For example, a level 10 orc will ignore a level 60 standing
    next to it.&nbsp; The orc will attack a level 60 that sits down next to
    it.&nbsp; (And then will promptly be slain).&nbsp; Some creatures will
    attack all hostile targets regardless of level.&nbsp; Skeletons and other
    undead do this in many zones.&nbsp;</li>
  <li>As above, some mobs will ignore a call for help.&nbsp; That is, if a level
    60 walks into an level 20 orc camp and smacks one of them, the orc that was
    attacked will scream for help.&nbsp; The rest of the camp will most likely
    just pretend not to notice.&nbsp; (While secretly hoping they are not next).</li>
  <li>Harmony will reduce the orange circle to a radius of near zero for a short
    time.&nbsp; During that period, the harmonized mob will not answer calls for
    help.&nbsp; It will of course respond like normal if directly
    attacked.&nbsp; Note that a harmonized mob will attack if a hostile target
    occupies its physical space.&nbsp; (If you bump into an aggressive,
    harmonized mob, it will attack)</li>
  <li>Not all mobs are social.&nbsp; (call for help or answer calls for help)</li>
</ol>
<div align="center">
  <center>
  <table border="1" cellpadding="3">
    <tr>
      <td><img border="0" src="images/aggro1.gif"></td>
      <td>In this example, the <b>M</b>agician is outside the aggro radius of
        the mob <b>X</b>.&nbsp; The <b>P</b>et is moving to the magician's
        location on a path right over the top of mob X.
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p>The pet will <u> never</u> cause mob X to attack in this situation.&nbsp;</p>
        <p><u>Aggro Theory at this point:</u> </p>
        <ol>
          <li>Mob X will only attack a pet if the pet attacks Mob X first (melee, spell
            or taunt) </li>
        </ol>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><img border="0" src="images/aggro2.gif"></td>
      <td>In this example, the <b>M</b>agician sends the <b>P</b>et to attack
        Mob <b>Y</b>.&nbsp; The pet does not taunt or cast before arriving at
        Mob Y's location.
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p>Mob Y will respond by attacking the Pet, but as long as it's call for
        help radius does not include Mob X's physical location, Mob X will not
        attack.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
        <p>Note that the pet is standing within Mob X's attack radius.&nbsp;
        However, since the pet has not attacked Mob X -- and Mob X is a bit too
        far away from Mob Y to hear it's call for help, Mob X does nothing.</p>
        <p><u>Aggro Theory at this point:</u> </p>
        <ol>
          <li>Mob X will only attack a pet if the pet attacks Mob X first (melee, spell
            or taunt) </li>
          <li>Mob X will not attack a pet simply because the pet is attacking a
            social mob to which it is sympathetic -- even if the pet is
            attacking within Mob X's normal aggro radius</li>
        </ol>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><img border="0" src="images/aggro3.gif"></td>
      <td>This example is the same as the above, however the <b>P</b>et pauses
        to cast a spell or taunts Mob <b>Y</b>.
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p>Mob Y will move to attack the Pet.&nbsp; Since it's path to
        the Pet takes it's call for help radius across Mob X's physical
        location, Mob X will join the fight.</p>
        <p><u>Aggro Theory at this point:</u> </p>
        <ol>
          <li>Mob X will only attack a pet if the pet attacks Mob X first (melee, spell
            or taunt) </li>
          <li>Mob X will not attack a pet simply because the pet is attacking a
            social mob to which it is sympathetic -- even if the pet is
            attacking within Mob X's normal aggro radius </li>
          <li>Mob X will attack a pet if a call for help can be heard by social, sympathetic mobs
            physically inside the call for help radius -- pet position is
            unimportant.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p>&nbsp;</td>
    </tr>
  </table>
